0199|- [HelpText]
0200|#STRDIST L1,L2
0201|*computes Levenshtein distance
0202|*between strings given on edit lines L1,L2.
0203|- shadow W: [LINK(http://www.merriampark.com/ld.htm)] [/LINK]
0204|*See e.g. www.merriampark.com/ld.htm
S   |          WWWWWWWWWWWWWWWWWWWWWWWWWW
0206|*Levenshtein (edit) distance is a measure of the similarity between two
0207|*strings s and t. The distance is the number of deletions, insertions, or
0208|*substitutions required to transform s into t.
0209|*Levenshtein distance is named after the Russian scientist Vladimir
0210|*Levenshtein, who devised the algorithm in 1965.
0212|*The Levenshtein distance algorithm has been used in
0213|*Spell checking, Speech recognition, DNA analysis, Plagiarism detection,
0214|*etc.
0216|*In Survo, Levenshtein distance is used for detecting typos in command and
0217|- shadow %: [LINK(q01_13.html)] [/LINK]
0218|*specification words (see ERROR?) and in heuristic searches by
S   |                          %%%%%
0219|- shadow %: [LINK(q05_19.html)] [/LINK]
0220|*the FIND command (see HFIND?).
S   |                       %%%%%
0221|*The standard measure is slightly modified by permitting an interchange of
0222|*two consecutive characters as one of the edit operations.
0224|*Example:
0225|*STRDIST CUR+1,CUR+2 / Levenshtein distance is 2 (1)
0226|*HEIGHTS
0227|*HEIGTHS
0229|*Thus the original distance is 2 (2 substitutions) and the modified
0230|*one is 1 (1 interchange).
